'''''Poquita Ropa''''' ({{lang-en|''Few Clothes''}}) is the twelfth [[studio album]] by [[Guatemala]]n [[singer]]-[[songwriter]] [[Ricardo Arjona]]. It was released on August 24, 2010 through [[Warner Music]]. It was recorded in [[Mexico City]], [[New York]], and [[Los Angeles]] and was produced by Lee Levin and Dan Warner under their production name Los Gringo, with additional works from [[Matt Rollings]] and [[Brian Lang]].

A drastic change from his previous albums, ''Poquita Ropa'' was produced trying to use the least number of [[musical instrument]]s as possible. Arjona's goal was to produce the songs "almost as they were born", this was done by using nonexistent sounds giving them a more acoustic-feel. With this, the singer achieved a production style that seemed to be [[a capella]] performances, commenting that "music and women look better with little clothes."

Critically and commercially successful, it became his third number-one set on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] and Latin Pop Albums chart, and also topped the lists in [[CAPIF|Argentina]] and [[AMPROFON|Mexico]]. The album was certified Platinum in Argentina and Mexico, and reached Gold status in Chile, Colombia and the United States. The album was nominated at the [[53rd Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]]. ''Poquita Ropa'' was given generally positive reviews. Jason Birchmeier of [[Allmusic]] considered the album a "stripped-down acoustic effort" though stating that it was "impressive".

''Poquita Ropa'' spawned three singles. "[[Puente (song)|Puente]]", a song with Cuban influences, was released as the [[lead single]] off the album and peaked at No. 36 on the ''Billboard'' [[Latin Pop Songs]] chart. The other two singles released were "[[Vida (song)|Vida]]" and "[[Marta (song)|Marta]]", both of which failed to gain success on charts. Instead of embarking on another worldwide tour, Arjona promoted the album with an eponymous film. It was broadcasted on [[HBO]] and [[A&E Network|A&E]], and were directed by Joaqu<U+00ED>n Cambre, and features Mexican [[Soap opera|telenovela]] actress [[Edith Gonz<U+00E1>lez]].

== Composition ==
{{Quote box
| quote  = "The musicians and engineers who were involved in [the recording process of] ''Poquita Ropa'', they are the best of [[Los Angeles, CA|Los Angeles]], [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] and [[Miami, Florida|Miami]]. This is very important for an artist that has nothing to prove and that constantly breaks the rules of commercial music."
:<U+2014>Dan Warner.<ref name=puente1/>
| width  = 20em
| align  = left
| quoted = 1
}}
In ''Poquita Ropa'', Arjona drastically changed his musical style. Arjona tried to use the least number of instruments as possible. The result was a production that seems to be a capella performances. Arjona has commented about this album that "music and women look better with little clothes."<ref name=unionradio1>[http://www.unionradio.net/ActualidadUR/Nota/visorNota.aspx?id=52024&tpCont=1 "Arjona desnuda sus canciones en "Poquita ropa"] (in Spanish). Union Radio. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> He further commented that "they [the songs] are like women, they get things up and are so concerned about this that they forget that the less clothes, more beauty. The songs are often overwhelmed by ourselves, because we saturate them with arrangements looking to exalt their qualities and we end up hiding them."<ref name=unionradio1/> 

Production was handled by Arjona himself and Dan Warner, who has worked with [[Shakira]], [[Celine Dion]] and [[Christina Aguilera]].<ref name=puente1>[http://www.nacion.com/2010-08-09/Entretenimiento/NotaPrincipal/v09-GERAR-MUSICA1.aspx "Ricardo Arjona tiende hoy su Puente"]. ''[[La Naci<U+00F3>n]]''. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> Jason Birchmeier from [[Allmusic]] commented that ''Poquita Ropa'' "finds Arjona at his most naked, backed by spare [[musical arrangements|arrangements]] of [[acoustic guitar]], piano, and [[Hammond B-3]] along with occasional touches of [[string instrument|strings]], [[woodwinds]], and chorus vocals."<ref name="birchmeier">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1841995|pure_url=yes}}|title= Poquita Ropa > Review| first=Jason|last=Birchmeier |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] |work= [[Allmusic]]|accessdate=7 September 2010}}</ref> ''Poquita Ropa'' marked the first time that [[Tommy Torres]] did not work with Arjona, whose last production was for ''[[5to Piso]]'' (2008). The album is mainly similar to Arjona's work on ''[[Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe]]'' (2000).<ref name="birchmeier"/>

"[[Puente (song)|Puente]]", the [[lead single]], has a length of eight minutes and thirty seconds and is divided in three parts. The first one is a cappella song, sang mainly with a piano. The second part is a ballad with [[Caribbean music|caribbean]] and [[Latin music|Latin sounds]], with some [[Salsa music|salsa]] and [[Cuban music|Cuban-influences]].<ref>[http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldetoluca/notas/n1739751.htm "Le canta al pueblo cubano"] (in Spanish). ''El Sol de Toluca''. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> The third is a mixture of salsa and [[merengue music|merengue]], with Cuban-influences.  M<U+00F3>nica Maristain from newspaper ''[[La Naci<U+00F3>n]]'' compared it with a 1999 song by [[Fito P<U+00E1>ez]], "Habana".<ref name="habana">Maristain, M<U+00F3>nica (19 July 2010). [http://www.nacion.com/2010-07-29/Entretenimiento/UltimaHora/Entretenimiento2465948.aspx "Ricardo Arjona se pone tropical en su nuevo disco"] (in Spanish). [[La Naci<U+00F3>n]]. Retrieved on 11 May 2012.</ref>

===Lyrical content===
[[File:Centro Habana (Cropped).jpg|thumb|250px|[[La Habana]] is the main theme in lead single "[[Puente (song)|Puente]]", which talks about two separated brothers.]]
When asked about "Puente"'s main theme, Arjona commented: "Although many believe is a treshed topic, it isn't for a cuban, be it on the island or Florida. The status of this dispute hasn't changed since 1959 and i've never seen something as disgusting as a rivality between people occasionated from politics. [[Hugo Ch<U+00E1>vez|Ch<U+00E1>vez]] can fight with [[<U+00C1>lvaro Uribe|Uribe]], [[Fidel Castro|Fidel]] with [[Barack Obama|Obama]], but what has this to do with two third-generation cousins that inherit an enmity for a politic matter[?]".<ref name="Arjona-Puente">[http://www.elcolombiano.com/BancoConocimiento/A/arjona_canta_ahora_con_poquita_ropa/arjona_canta_ahora_con_poquita_ropa.asp "Arjona canta ahora con poquita ropa"] (in Spanish). ''[[El Colombiano]]''. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref>  In the song, Arjona sings: "Habana / siempre en las mitades, tan mitad espa<U+00F1>ola, tan mitad africana / saben bien las olas que en cada ventana siempre hay un testigo / Habana."<ref name="habana"/> He also commented that "Puente" was the only song "not allowed to undress".<ref name=unionradio1/><ref name="PUSA">[http://www.elperiodicousa.com/noticia/11730/poquita-ropa-es-el-disco-que-siempre-quiso-hacer-arjona "<U+201C>Poquita ropa<U+201D> es el disco que siempre quiso hacer: Arjona"] (in Spanish). El Peri<U+00F3>dico USA. Retrieved on 11 May 2012.</ref>

"[[Vida (song)|Vida]]", the second single, is considered by Arjona as an autobiographical song. He further commented that it "contains a good dose of the life of my old man", as a reference to his father, Don Ricardo Arjona, who died in 2010.<ref name="Arjona1">[http://www.prensalibre.com/noticias/Arjona_triunfa_Vida_poquita_ropa_0_375562533.html "Arjona triunfa con "Vida", su nuevo sencillo"] (in Spanish). ''[[Prensa Libre]]''. Retrieved on April 19, 2012.</ref> In an interview, music video director Joaqu<U+00ED>n Cambre commented that "'Vida' is a sweet song, exciting and bitter nonetheless. I tried to represent that mix of feelings crafting an ambience  of hope inside of a story that inetivably has a tragic end. Ricardo Arjona plays the song while listening to the story playing on a old disc."<ref>[http://www.pronto.com.ar/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=24534&Itemid=362 "Arjona: "Vida es un tema autobiogr<U+00E1>fico y con una enorme dosis de la vida de mi viejo"] (in Spanish). Pronto. Argentina: Magallanes Media. Retrieved on April 19, 2012.</ref> On "[[Marta (song)|Marta]]", Arjona commented that it is "one of those songs with brushworks related to something that happened, put on the [[magnifying glass]] of the author."<ref name=unionradio1/> When asked if "Escribir Una Canci<U+00F3>n" could be considered a guide for songwriters, he stated that "there are no guides to write songs. If any, songwriters would stop writing songs and start writing guides."<ref name=unionradio1/> 

Arjona also talked about "Mi Pa<U+00ED>s", commenting that the song was "the story of anybody who left their land and searched for life in another place, with all that huge dose of nostalgia and memory those moments carries." He also stated that he wrote the song when he left Guatemala.<ref name=unionradio1/> "Que Voy A Hacer Conmigo" was originally included as a rock song on his 1991 album ''[[Del Otro Lado del Sol]]'', but the lyrics were slightly changed on the new version. Arjona stated that it was a difficult process to leave the songs "almost as they were born", stating that he had to convince the people who worked on the album that "it was the way the songs were to be", without adding any sounds.<ref name="PUSA"/>

== Release and promotion ==
''Poquita Ropa'' was first released in Spain on 6 August 2010.<ref name="SP"/> It was later available in the United States, Latin America and Europe on 15 August 2010.<ref name="USIT"/> The compact disc version of the album was released in the United States, the United Kingdom and Latin America on 24 August 2010.<ref name="USCD"/> A deluxe edition was released on iTunes, and contained the track "Estas Ganas de Llorar".

=== Singles ===
{{Listen
 |filename     = Ricardo_Arjona_Puente_(Caribe).ogg
 |title        = "Puente" (Caribe)
 |description  = A sample of "Puente", displaying the third musical change.
 |filename2     = Ricardo_Arjona_Marta.ogg
 |title2        = "Marta"
 |description2  = A sample of "Marta", displaying the first chorus as asang by Arjona.
}}
The lead single off the album "Puente", was released on 9 August 2010.<ref>[http://www.am.com.mx/Nota.aspx?ID=419547 Peri<U+00F3>dico A.M. - Construye Arjona su 'Puente'] (in Spanish). ''Peri<U+00F3>dico A.M''. Period<U+00ED>stica Meridiano. Retrieved on 11 May 2012.</ref> The song is a political-charged anthem to Havana, Cuba's capital city, the relationships between Cuba and the United States, the international economical blockade against the island and the Cuban invasions to Florida. The song reached No. 36 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Latin Pop Songs]] chart. "Puente" remains one of the least successful lead singles by Arjona. The music video was filmed between Mexico and Argentina.<ref>[http://www.nacion.com/2010-08-09/Entretenimiento/NotaPrincipal/v09-GERAR-MUSICA1.aspx "Ricardo Arjona tiende hoy su ''Puente''"] (in Spanish). [[La Naci<U+00F3>n]]. Retrieved on April 19, 2012.</ref>

The second single released was "Vida", on 7 December 2010. Its music video was filmed in Mexico and directed by Argentinian filmmaker Joaqu<U+00ED>n Cambre.<ref name="Arjona1"/> The third and last single from the album was "Marta", released on 29 March 2011. It became the second consecutive single of ''Poquita Ropa'' not to chart in the United States. The accompanying music video featured Mexican [[Soap opera|telenovela]] actress [[Edith Gonz<U+00E1>lez]].<ref>[http://www.record.com.mx/circo/2011-04-05/edith-gonzalez-baila-para-arjona "Edith Gonz<U+00E1>lez baila para Arjona"] (in Spanish). ''Record'' (Mexico). Retrieved on April 19, 2012.</ref>

=== Film ===
On 12 February 2011, [[HBO]] premiered the film ''Poquita Ropa <U+2013> Una Historia Apasionada''.<ref name="HBO">[http://www.diariocolatino.com/es/20110218/amigos/89605/Ricardo-Arjona-en-cortometraje.htm "Ricardo Arjona en cortometraje"] (in Spanish). Diario CoLatino (Sociedad Cooperativa de Empleados de Diario Latino de R.L.). Retrieved on 11 May 2012.</ref> The film is a compilation of music videos for all the songs on the album, interlaced under one story and with a duration of 67 minutes.<ref name="HBO"/> It was directed by Joaqu<U+00ED>n Cambre,<ref name=PR4>{{cite web|title=Protagoniza <U+201C>Poquita ropa<U+201D> la nueva pel<U+00ED><U+00AD>cula de HBO|url=http://www.noticias24.com/gente/noticia/16333/protagoniza-poquita-ropa-la-nueva-pelicula-para-television-de-hbo/|work=Noticias24|accessdate=5 June 2012|language=Spanish}}</ref> and co-starred Arjona, Gonz<U+00E1>lez, Edgar Vivar, Daniel Arenas, Mimi Morales and Kenny.<ref name="Notisistema">[http://www.notisistema.com/noticias/?p=364810 "Arjona y Edith Gonz<U+00E1>lez comparten escenario"] (in Spanish). Notisistema. Retrieved on April 19, 2012.</ref> ''Poquita Ropa <U+2013> Una Historia Apasionada'' was produced in Argentina<ref name="HBO"/> and Mexico.<ref name="A&E">[http://www.el-nacional.com/www/site/p_contenido.php?q=nodo/198144/Arte%20y%20Espect%C3%A1culos/A&E-ofrece-programaci%C3%B3n-especial-de-Ricardo-Arjona "A&E ofrece programaci<U+00F3>n especial de Ricardo Arjona"] (in Spanish). [[El Nacional (Venezuela)|''El Nacional'']]. Retrieved on 11 May 2012.</ref> Jes<U+00FA>s Grovas, HBO's Corporative Communication manager for Mexico and Central America commented that it was "a pleasure to have on screen the music of a songwriter like Ricardo Arjona, which is warranty of quality".<ref name="HBO"/> It was also broadcasted by [[A&E Network|A&E]].<ref name="terra">[http://www.terra.com.mx/musica/articulo/1082249/Ricardo+Arjona+y+Edith+Gonzalez+estrenan+video+clip.htm "Ricardo Arjona y Edith Gonz<U+00E1>lez estrenan video clip"] (in Spanish). Terra Mexico. Retrieved on April 19, 2012.</ref><ref name="A&E"/>

== Reception ==
=== Commercial performance ===
''Poquita Ropa'' debuted atop the ''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums chart, on the week ending 11 September 2010,<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/latin-albums?chartDate=2010-09-11 "Top Latin Albums of the week"]. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. United States: [[Prometheus Global Media]]. Retrieved on 10 May 2012.</ref> becoming Arjona's third studio album to reach No. 1 on that chart, following ''[[Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe]]'' (2000) and ''[[5to Piso]]'' (2008). The following week, it fell to No. 2, as [[Enrique Iglesias]]' ''[[Euphoria (Enrique Iglesias album)|Euphoria]]'' rocovered the top position.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/latin-albums?chartDate=2010-09-18 "Top Latin Albums of the week"]. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. United States: [[Prometheus Global Media]]. Retrieved on 10 May 2012.</ref> ''Poquita Ropa'' debuted atop the [[Latin Pop Albums]] on the week ending 11 September 2010.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/latin-pop-albums?chartDate=2010-09-11 "Latin Pop Albums of the week"]. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. United States: [[Prometheus Global Media]]. Retrieved on 10 May 2012.</ref> It became Arjona's fourth album to reach No. 1, after ''Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe'', ''5to Piso'' and ''[[Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer]]'' (2007). ''Poquita Ropa'' also debuted at No. 43 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming the his highest entry on that chart.<ref name=BB200>{{cite news|title=Ricardo Arjona Album & Songs Chart History <U+2013> Billboard 200|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/ricardo-arjona/chart-history/29908?f=305&g=Albums|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=9 June 2012|location=United States}}</ref> Overseas, the album was also commercially successful. In Mexico, ''Poquita Ropa'' debuted at No. 29.<ref>[http://mexicancharts.com/archive.asp?todo=show&woche=34&jahr=2010&sparte=a "Mexican Charts"]. Mexican Charts (Hung Medien). Retrieved on 10 May 2012.</ref> and jumped to No.1 in its second week.<ref name="Mexican Charts">[http://mexicancharts.com/archive.asp?todo=show&woche=36&jahr=2010&sparte=a "Mexican Charts"]. Mexican Charts (Hung Medien). Retrieved on 10 May 2012.</ref> It remained at No. 1 for two consecutive weeks, before dropping to No. 5.<ref name="Mexican Charts"/><ref>[http://mexicancharts.com/archive.asp?todo=show&woche=35&jahr=2010&sparte=a "Mexican Charts"]. Mexican Charts (Hung Medien). Retrieved on 10 May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://mexicancharts.com/archive.asp?todo=show&woche=37&jahr=2010&sparte=a "Mexican Charts"]. Mexican Charts (Hung Medien). Retrieved on 10 May 2012.</ref> ''Poquita Ropa'' also peaked at No. 1 in Argentina, and No. 2 in Chile.<ref name=poquita/> On the 2010 year-end chart, ''Poquita Ropa'' was the 43rd best-selling album on the Latin Albums chart,<ref name="LAF"/> and the 12th best-selling album on the Latin Pop Albums chart.<ref name="LPAF"/> In Mexico, the album was the 31st best-selling album of 2010.<ref name="YEMX"/>

''Poquita Ropa'' was awarded a [[Platinum certification]] by the [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]] (CAPIF), denoting 40,000 copies sold.<ref name="CAPIF">[http://www.capif.org.ar/Default.asp?PerDesde_MM=0&PerDesde_AA=0&PerHasta_MM=0&PerHasta_AA=0&interprete=Ricardo+Arjona&album=Poquita+Ropa&LanDesde_MM=0&LanDesde_AA=0&LanHasta_MM=0&LanHasta_AA=0&Galardon=O&Tipo=1&ACCION2=+Buscar+&ACCION=Buscar&CO=5&CODOP=ESOP "Argentinian album certifications <U+2013> Ricardo Arjona <U+2013> Poquita Ropa"]. Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers.</ref><ref name="cert2">[http://www.informador.com.mx/entretenimiento/2010/230567/6/debuta-ricardo-arjona-en-listas-de-ventas-de-eu.htm "Debuta Ricardo Arjona en listas de ventas de EU"] (in Spanish). [[El Informador (Mexico)|''El Informador'' (Mexico)]]. Retrieved on 10 May 2012.</ref> It was also certified Platinum by the [[Mexican Association of Producers of Phonograms and Videograms]] (AMPROFON), denoting 60,000 copies sold.<ref name="cert2"/><ref name="AMPROFON">[http://www.amprofon.com.mx/certificaciones.php?artista=Ricardo+Arjona&titulo=Poquita+Ropa&categoria=ALBUM&contenido=buscar "Mexican album certifications <U+2013> Ricardo Arjona <U+2013> Poquita Ropa"](in Spanish). [[Asociaci<U+00F3>n Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas]].</ref> In the United States, ''Poquita Ropa'' was certified Gold (Latin) by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting 50,000 copies shipped.<ref name="cert2"/> In Chile and Colombia, the album was awarded a gold certification denoting 5,000 and 10,000 copies sold, respectively.<ref name="cert2"/>

=== Critical response ===
{{Album ratings
| rev1 = [[Allmusic]] 
| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name="birchmeier"/>
}}
Jason Birchmeier of Allmusic gave the album a positive review, saying that it was a "stripped-down acoustic effort" yet considering it "impressive".<ref name="birchmeier"/> An editor from ''El Carabobe<U+00F1>o'' stated that ''Poquita Ropa'' was "an album of ghetto and concept, with flawless production and carried out with the right amount of instruments."<ref>[http://www.el-carabobeno.com/espectculos/articulo/4784/arjona-a-los-grammys-con-poquita-ropa "Arjona a los Grammys con <U+201C>Poquita Ropa<U+201D>"]. ''El Carabobe<U+00F1>o'' (Editora El Carabobe<U+00F1>o C.A.). Retrieved on 11 May 2012.</ref>
